        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Chain Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Chain Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Chain Conveyors: Drag, Overhead, Slat & Apron
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A chain conveyor uses one or more endless chains as the primary conveying medium to move products along a fixed path. Chain conveyors handle heavy loads, high temperatures, and harsh environments where <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">belt conveyors</a> and <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a> cannot operate. The four main categories are drag chain (bulk material in troughs), <a href="/conveyor-types/chain-conveyors/overhead/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">overhead chain</a> (suspended loads on monorail or power-and-free tracks), slat chain (flat surfaces on parallel chains), and apron chain (overlapping pans for bulk or unit loads).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Drag Chain Conveyors -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="drag-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Drag Chain</div>
      <h2 id="drag-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Drag Chain <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>A drag chain conveyor pulls bulk material through an enclosed trough using one or more chains with attached flights, paddles, or scrapers. The chain travels along the trough bottom, dragging material from the inlet to the discharge point. The enclosed design contains dust, prevents contamination, and allows horizontal, inclined, and combination path configurations.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">En-Masse Drag Conveyors</h3>
        <p>En-masse drag conveyors move bulk material as a continuous column (en masse) within a rectangular or round trough. The chain and flights occupy only 10-15% of the trough cross-section. The material column moves as a slug, with internal friction between particles carrying the load rather than the flights alone. This reduces chain loading and wear compared to conventional scraper conveyors. En-masse conveyors handle 10-500 tons per hour of dry bulk materials like grain, cement, ash, and chemical powders.</p>
        <p>CDM Systems, Hapman, and KWS Manufacturing produce en-masse drag conveyors for food, chemical, and mineral processing applications. For detailed specifications, see our <a href="/conveyor-types/drag-chain-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">drag chain conveyor guide</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Tubular Drag Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors use a chain with evenly spaced circular discs that pull material through a sealed tube. The discs fit closely within the tube bore and push material ahead of each disc as the chain moves. Tubular drag systems handle fragile materials (nuts, snack foods, pet food) with minimal product degradation because the material moves gently as a plug between discs rather than being scraped or scooped.</p>
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors route through 3D paths , horizontal runs, vertical lifts, and multiple direction changes within a single continuous loop. Cablevey Conveyors (now Cablevey by WAMGROUP) and Hapman specialize in tubular drag systems for food and pharmaceutical applications. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/drag-chain-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">drag chain conveyor page</a> for detailed tubular drag coverage.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Cablevey is now part of WAMGROUP -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Overhead Chain Conveyors -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="overhead-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Overhead Chain</div>
      <h2 id="overhead-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Overhead Chain <span class="text-accent">Conveyor Systems</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Overhead chain conveyors suspend products from trolleys that ride on an elevated track, carrying loads through production processes while keeping the floor clear. The chain drives the trolleys along the track at controlled speeds. Two main types serve different application needs: <a href="/conveyor-types/monorail-power-free/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">monorail (continuous-speed) and power-and-free</a> (variable-speed with accumulation).</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Monorail Overhead Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Monorail systems use a single track with chain-driven trolleys moving at constant speed. All trolleys travel at the same speed in the same direction. Monorail conveyors suit continuous-flow processes like paint lines, powder coating, and drying ovens where products need uniform exposure time. They handle loads from 10 to 2,000 lbs per trolley. Jervis B. Webb (Daifuku), Richards-Wilcox, and Pacline manufacture monorail overhead systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Power-and-Free Overhead Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Power-and-free systems use two tracks: a powered track with a continuously moving chain, and a free track where trolleys can be engaged or disengaged from the chain independently. This allows individual trolleys to stop, accumulate, switch tracks, and travel at different speeds. Power-and-free conveyors serve complex assembly lines where products require different dwell times at different stations.</p>
        <p>Power-and-free systems handle the most complex routing in manufacturing: multiple speed zones, accumulation buffers, spurs for offline processing, elevation changes, and merging from multiple lines. They are the backbone of automotive assembly, heavy equipment manufacturing, and complex finishing operations. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/chain-conveyors/overhead/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">overhead conveyor systems guide</a> for complete coverage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Slat Chain Conveyors -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="slat-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Slat Chain</div>
      <h2 id="slat-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Slat Chain <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>A slat chain conveyor uses flat metal, wood, or plastic slats attached between two parallel chains. The chains ride in guides on either side of the conveyor frame, and the slats form a continuous flat surface between the chains. Products ride on the slat surface. The chain drive pulls the slats and products from the tail (loading) end to the head (discharge) end.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Metal Slat Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Steel <a href="/conveyor-types/slat-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">slat conveyors</a> handle the heaviest loads: pallets (2,000-10,000 lbs), engine blocks, castings, and heavy assemblies. The steel slats provide a rigid, flat surface that supports concentrated point loads without deflection. Slat width ranges from 6 to 60 inches. Chain pitch and slat thickness scale with load capacity. Metal slat conveyors operate at 10-60 FPM in assembly lines, paint systems, and heavy manufacturing.</p>
        <p>Metal slat conveyors withstand high temperatures (oven curing, paint bake), heavy impacts (part loading by crane or robot), and chemical exposure (wash systems, coating lines). They last decades in demanding environments with regular chain lubrication and slat replacement as the primary maintenance items.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Plastic Modular Chain (Table-Top Chain)</h3>
        <p>Plastic modular chain conveyors use interlocking plastic links that form a flat conveying surface. The chain runs in a plastic or stainless steel frame without separate slats , the chain itself is the surface. Table-top chain conveyors handle light to moderate loads (1-100 lbs per product) at speeds of 10-200 FPM. They serve <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food packaging lines</a>, pharmaceutical packaging, and consumer goods packaging where sanitary design, low noise, and gentle product handling matter.</p>
        <p>Rexnord, Intralox, Habasit, and Uni-Chain (Ammeraal Beltech) supply table-top chain components. System integrators including Dorner and mk North America build complete table-top chain conveyor systems. The modular design allows curves, inclines, and declines within a single chain run without transfer points.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Current brand ownership of Uni-Chain and Ammeraal Beltech -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Hinged Steel Belt (Chip Conveyor)</h3>
        <p><a href="/conveyor-types/hinged-steel-belt/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Hinged steel belt conveyors</a> use overlapping steel slats hinged at the edges, forming a continuous belt-like surface. They handle hot chips, scrap metal, and debris from machining operations. The hinged construction allows the belt to conform to the conveyor path including inclines. Chip conveyors are specialized slat chain variants common in metalworking but occasionally used in packaging for handling sharp, hot, or abrasive waste materials.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Apron Chain Conveyors -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apron-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Apron Chain</div>
      <h2 id="apron-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Apron Chain <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Apron chain conveyors (also called pan conveyors) use overlapping metal pans attached to parallel chains. The pans overlap to form a continuous trough that carries bulk materials or heavy unit loads. The overlap prevents material leakage between pans. Apron conveyors handle the most demanding bulk material conditions: hot clinker, sharp rock, heavy castings, and abrasive ores.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Heavy-Duty Apron Feeders</h3>
        <p>Apron feeders use extra-heavy chain and thick manganese steel pans to receive material from hoppers, bins, and crushers. They meter material from storage onto downstream conveyors at controlled rates. Apron feeders handle 100-5,000 tons per hour of rock, ore, coal, and aggregate. Pan widths range from 24 to 96 inches. Metso, FLSmidth, and thyssenkrupp manufacture mining and aggregate apron feeders.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Metso, FLSmidth, thyssenkrupp current apron feeder product lines -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Light-Duty Apron Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Light-duty apron conveyors handle lighter bulk materials and unit loads in manufacturing and packaging. They feed <a href="/conveyor-types/bucket-elevators/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bucket elevators</a>, <a href="/conveyor-types/screw-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">screw conveyors</a>, and processing equipment. Light apron conveyors also serve as <a href="/industries/assembly-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">assembly line conveyors</a> where the flat pan surface carries workpieces through manual or automated assembly stations at 5-20 FPM.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
