  <!-- Selection Guide -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Select a <span class="text-accent">Chain Conveyor</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Material type drives the category.</strong> Bulk materials need drag chain or apron chain. Suspended unit loads need overhead chain. Floor-level unit loads need slat chain. Lightweight packaged goods need table-top chain. Each category uses fundamentally different chain configurations and frame designs.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Load weight and size determine chain specification.</strong> Chain pitch (distance between links), pin diameter, plate thickness, and material grade scale with the load. Standard conveyor chains (ANSI or ISO rated) cover most applications. Custom-engineered chains handle extreme loads and environments. Always specify chain with a safety factor of 6-10x the calculated chain pull.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Standard chain safety factor recommendation 6-10x -->

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Environment dictates material and lubrication.</strong> Standard carbon steel chain works in clean, dry environments. Stainless steel chain serves food, pharmaceutical, and corrosive environments. High-temperature alloy chain handles oven and furnace applications. Self-lubricating chains (sintered bronze bushings) eliminate external lubrication in clean or food-grade environments.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Routing complexity determines overhead system type.</strong> Simple continuous loops use monorail. Complex routing with accumulation, spurs, speed changes, and merging requires power-and-free. The cost difference between monorail and power-and-free is substantial, so match the system capability to the actual routing requirements.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Maintenance commitment matters.</strong> Chain conveyors require regular lubrication, chain tension adjustment, and wear inspection. Budget for chain replacement at 5-15 year intervals depending on load and speed. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a> and <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">belt conveyors</a> require less maintenance for lighter loads. Use chain conveyors only where the application demands it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

